      <scopecontent id="aspace_4bd93745249a9e61182fb41fef53fb9e">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The papers comprise images captured during Richard Gamble Knight's tenure from 1957 to 1961 as an employee of the architectural firm Eero Saarinen and Associates, and during other periods of Knight's life, such as his student years.  Consisting of photographic prints, negatives, and slides, the images range from projects designed by Saarinen and Associates (including Dulles International Airport, John Deere and Company, Trans World Flight Center, CBS Building in New York, and Morse and Stiles Colleges at Yale University), to candid shots of Saarinen and his employees at work and socializing, to photographic studies of architectural forms and details.  Also included in the papers are audio recordings of interviews Knight conducted with five former Saarinen employees for his book, <title>
               <part>Saarinen's Quest: A Memoir</part>
            </title>, published in 2008.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <relatedmaterial id="aspace_2557a30a04235f1eb0c097f37ea3d371">
         <head>Related Materials</head>
         <p>Eero Saarinen Collection (MS 593).</p>  
      </relatedmaterial>
      <bioghist id="aspace_2cf0f84f76a544557bc5f960f9f9cf9d">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Born in Flint, Michigan, on November 29, 1926, Richard Gamble Knight studied engineering and architecture at the University of Michigan (BS Engineering, 1951), the Cranbrook Academy of Art, and Lawrence Technical University (BS Architecture, 1957) in Southfield, Michigan.  In 1957, Knight was hired as a junior architectural designer at Eero Saarinen and Associates in Bloomfield Hills, Michigan, where he worked until Saarinen's death in 1961.  A budding photographer as well as an architect, Knight succeeded Balthazar Korab as the firm's "court photographer," documenting the design process for clients and creating a visual record of the firm's activities and creative output.  After Saarinen's death in 1961, Knight continued his career as an architect, and also took on roles as a graphic and interior designer, an instructor of design, a writer, and a prolific multimedia artist whose works were exhibited regularly.  In 2008, Knight published <title>
               <part>Saarinen's Quest: A Memoir</part>
            </title> (San Francisco: William Stout Publishers), which focuses on Knight's time at Eero Saarinen and Associates, and features many of the photographs Knight took while employed at the firm.  Knight died on December 16, 2008, in Alameda, California.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_f628043ea8b9fd4bb210fda4756ad488">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The materials are open for research.</p>
         <p>Original audiovisual materials, as well as preservation and duplicating masters, may not be played.  Researchers must consult use copies, or if none exist must pay for a use copy, which is retained by the repository.  Researchers wishing to obtain an additional copy of non-commercially produced items for their personal use should consult the ordering reproductions information on the Manuscripts and Archives web site.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
